(1. INTELLECTUAL HERITAGE) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(1.1 MIT Athena and SPKI) show newline
(-----------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Cyberspace traces its lineage to MIT's Project Athena and the Simple) show newline
(Public Key Infrastructure \(SPKI\) work that emerged from MIT and the) show newline
(Internet Engineering Task Force \(IETF\).) show newline
() show newline
(Athena \(1983-1991\) introduced Kerberos, distributed authentication, and) show newline
(the concept of a unified computing environment across heterogeneous) show newline
(systems. Digital Equipment Corporation \(DEC\) funded Athena and) show newline
(contributed workstations.) show newline
() show newline
(Two independent threads merged at IETF to form SDSI/SPKI:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Simple Distributed Security Infrastructure \(SDSI\) - Ron Rivest at MIT, focusing on naming and local name spaces) show newline
(  * SPKI - Carl Ellison at IETF, focusing on authorization and capabilities) show newline
() show newline
(Ellison's SPKI RFCs \(2693, 2692\) formalized capability-based) show newline
(authorization through certificate chains. When IETF standardized this) show newline
(work, Rivest's SDSI naming merged in. The result \(SDSI/SPKI 2.0\) gave us) show newline
(both authorization and naming.) show newline
() show newline
(These ideas were absorbed during the same lamport epoch as R4RS Scheme) show newline
(\(1991\) and SDSI \(1996\), alongside the practical education of Boston) show newline
(traffic negotiation - both exercises in asserting authority without) show newline
(central coordination.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(1.2 Why Scheme) show newline
(--------------) show newline
() show newline
(Scheme was chosen because its homoiconic S-expressions make the) show newline
(representation of programs and structured data the same kind of thing.) show newline
(One parser, one set of tools works uniformly over code, certificates,) show newline
(audit trails, and configuration.) show newline
() show newline
(In a homoiconic language, the primary representation of programs is also) show newline
(a data structure in a primitive type of the language. Scheme uses) show newline
(S-expressions—nested lists and atoms—as both surface syntax and) show newline
(natural tree-shaped data. The abstract syntax tree and textual form) show newline
(closely align.) show newline
() show newline
(The same reader parses program text, configuration records, and) show newline
(application data into a single uniform format. Certificates, audit) show newline
(records, memos, and code are all S-expressions manipulated with the same) show newline
(combinators:) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(    ;; All the same representation) show newline
(    \(read\)           ; parse code) show newline
(    \(read-cert\)      ; parse certificate) show newline
(    \(read-audit\)     ; parse audit trail) show newline
(    \(kwic 'soup\)     ; search memos) show newline
() show newline
(One minimal, well-specified parser eliminates impedance mismatches) show newline
(between code format and data format. No JSON-to-object mapping. No) show newline
(protobuf schema compiler. Structures representing policies look exactly) show newline
(like structures representing the code enforcing them.) show newline
() show newline
(When you \(kwic 'soup\) you search S-expressions with S-expressions. The) show newline
(memos are data. The code is data. The boundary dissolves.) show newline
() show newline
(The language that Abelson and Sussman used to teach computational) show newline
(thinking at MIT is the same language used to implement the security) show newline
(architecture that MIT research defined. Full circle.) show newline
() show newline
(Cyberspace Scheme is intentionally R5RS and R7RS-small, following) show newline
(CHICKEN Scheme's philosophy: a small, portable core with extensions as) show newline
(libraries rather than language features. R5RS \(1998\) remains the most) show newline
(widely implemented Scheme standard. R7RS-small \(2013\) preserves that) show newline
(minimalist tradition while adding practical improvements like) show newline
(define-library. The large dialect \(R7RS-large, ongoing\) is explicitly) show newline
(avoided - complexity belongs in libraries, not the language) show newline
(specification.) show newline
() show newline
(CHICKEN was chosen over faster implementations \(Chez, Racket, Gambit\)) show newline
(for its elegance and deployment model. CHICKEN compiles to C, producing) show newline
(standalone executables with no runtime dependencies. The egg system) show newline
(provides a curated library ecosystem. Speed matters less than simplicity) show newline
(when the bottleneck is cryptographic operations in libsodium, not) show newline
(interpreter overhead.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
