(7. FORGE AND SMELTER) show newline
(------------------------------------------------------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(The forge module generates pronounceable passwords using Markov chains) show newline
(on digraph statistics. The lineage traces back to Multics.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.1 Heritage) show newline
(------------) show newline
() show newline
(Original design by Morrie Gasser in PL/1 on Multics. Gasser, author of) show newline
('Building a Secure Computer System' \(1988\), carried the code forward to) show newline
(VAX/VMS where it remained in PL/1 until the Alpha transition.) show newline
() show newline
(When DEC moved to Alpha architecture, PL/1 wasn't in the initial) show newline
(compiler release. The code had to be expunged from the TCB. Derrell) show newline
(Piper and Jon Callas rewrote it for VMS 6.0 \(circa 1991\): Piper wrote) show newline
(the BLISS system service for the Trusted Computing Base; Callas wrote) show newline
(the user-mode TPU smelter.) show newline
() show newline
(US and EU DEC patents were filed on the design \(now expired\). The) show newline
(terminology - forge, smelter - comes from metallurgy: the smelter) show newline
(refines raw ore \(word lists\) into workable material \(digraph) show newline
(statistics\); the forge shapes the final product \(pronounceable words\).) show newline
() show newline
(Callas later became a principal author of OpenPGP \(RFC 4880\) and) show newline
(co-founded PGP Corporation and Silent Circle. He remains a planned beta) show newline
(tester for Cyberspace.) show newline
() show newline
(The chain of custody: Gasser \(Multics PL/1\) → Piper/Callas \(VMS 6.0) show newline
(BLISS/TPU\) → Cyberspace \(Scheme\).) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.2 Design) show newline
(----------) show newline
() show newline
(The smelter reads word lists and extracts digraph \(character pair\)) show newline
(statistics:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Starting pair frequency - which pairs begin words) show newline
(  * Transition probability - given 'ab', what characters follow) show newline
(  * Termination markers - which pairs end words) show newline
() show newline
(The forge walks these statistics with weighted random selection,) show newline
(producing words that follow the phonetic patterns of the source) show newline
(language. Entropy is tracked in 'decibits' \(tenths of bits\) to quantify) show newline
(password strength.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.3 Languages) show newline
(-------------) show newline
() show newline
(Original VMS languages: English, Latin, Italian, Dutch, Sindarin,) show newline
(Webster. The VT100 diacriticals were encoded in DEC MCS \(Multinational) show newline
(Character Set\).) show newline
() show newline
(Cyberspace expansion to 40+ languages follows roughly the operational) show newline
(map of the Office of Strategic Services - another egg for those who) show newline
(recognize the geography:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Western Europe: French, German, Spanish, Portuguese) show newline
(  * Iberia: Catalan, Galician, Basque) show newline
(  * Nordic \(resistance networks\): Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Finnish) show newline
(  * Atlantic fringe: Irish, Welsh, Scottish Gaelic, Breton) show newline
(  * Balkans \(partisan country\): Greek, Albanian, Serbian, Croatian, Slovenian, Macedonian) show newline
(  * Eastern front: Polish, Czech, Slovak, Hungarian, Romanian) show newline
(  * Baltic: Lithuanian, Latvian, Estonian) show newline
(  * Soviet theater: Russian, Ukrainian, Bulgarian) show newline
(  * Near East: Turkish, Armenian) show newline
(  * Mediterranean \(George Cross island\): Maltese) show newline
(  * Detachment 101: Vietnamese, Thai, Lao, Korean) show newline
(  * Literary: Sindarin \(Tolkien's Elvish\), Dante's Divina Commedia) show newline
() show newline
(Word lists sourced from Hunspell, LibreOffice, SCOWL, OpenTaal, Eldamo,) show newline
(and the Princeton Dante Project. All diacriticals converted to UTF-8.) show newline
() show newline
(Sindarin preserves Tolkien's circumflexes: Manwë, Aulë, Andúril.) show newline
(Dante's medieval Italian sits alongside. The OSS framing is itself an) show newline
(easter egg - layers of meaning for those who dig.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.4 Related Standards) show newline
(---------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Forge predates but relates to two password generation standards:) show newline
() show newline
(  * FIPS 181 \(1993\) - Automated Password Generator. Uses trigraph \(3-letter\) statistics and hyphenation rules. More structured but less natural. Forge's digraph approach \(1991\) produces smoother results by learning from actual language patterns rather than syllable rules.) show newline
(  * OPIE/S/Key - One-time Passwords In Everything. Uses a fixed 2048-word dictionary optimized for spoken communication over phone lines. Words are short and phonetically distinct. Different goal: memorability for one-time use vs. pronounceability for permanent passwords.) show newline
() show newline
(Forge's contribution was combining Markov chain language modeling with) show newline
(entropy tracking - knowing not just that a password sounds right, but) show newline
(exactly how many bits of randomness it contains.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.5 Interface) show newline
(-------------) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(    \(forge\)              ; one English word) show newline
(    \(forge 5\)            ; five English words) show newline
(    \(forge 'sindarin\)    ; one Elvish word) show newline
(    \(forge 'latin 3\)     ; three Latin words) show newline
(    \(forge 'passphrase\)  ; 4-word passphrase) show newline
(    \(forge 'german 'passphrase 6\) ; 6-word German passphrase) show newline
() show newline
(Each word reports its entropy. Passphrases join words with hyphens. The) show newline
(forge is an easter egg - undocumented in help, discovered by schemers) show newline
(exploring the REPL.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.6 Cryptographic Entropy) show newline
(-------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(Passwords fall naturally out of pronounceable words when the entropy) show newline
(source is sound. Forge uses /dev/urandom for cryptographically secure) show newline
(randomness, not pseudo-random generators.) show newline
() show newline
(Boot-time verification runs automatically on module load:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Confirms /dev/urandom exists and is readable) show newline
(  * Reads 256 test bytes and checks byte distribution) show newline
(  * Verifies no single byte appears more than ~10% \(bias detection\)) show newline
(  * Confirms at least 100 distinct byte values \(diversity check\)) show newline
() show newline
(If verification fails, the module refuses to load. An easter egg with) show newline
(real security - someone exploring the REPL discovers \(forge\) and gets) show newline
(actual cryptographic passwords, not toys.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
(7.7 Audit Trail Heritage) show newline
(------------------------) show newline
() show newline
(The cryptographic audit trail \(Memo-0005\) descends from VMS) show newline
(SECURITY.AUDIT$JOURNAL and the cluster-wide security infrastructure of) show newline
(VMS 6.0 \(1993\). That system introduced:) show newline
() show newline
(  * SECURITY_POLICY bit 7 propagation) show newline
(  * Intrusion detection state replicated cluster-wide) show newline
(  * Breakin attempts detected across all nodes as one) show newline
(  * TLV-encoded object store) show newline
(  * The [000000]SECURITY.SYS file in ODS5 stored SECURITYCLASS records) show newline
() show newline
(The SECURITY_POLICY system parameter controlled C2/B1 security behavior:) show newline
() show newline
(Bit 7 in VMS 6.0 was cluster-wide security state propagation. When set,) show newline
(breakin detection and intrusion state replicated across all cluster) show newline
(nodes so N nodes behaved as one security domain.) show newline
() show newline
(The design principle then, as now: cluster nodes behave identically. N) show newline
(nodes, one security domain. Every significant action audited, every) show newline
(audit record signed.) show newline
() show newline
(Cyberspace audit trails apply the same principle at IPv6 scale.) show newline
() show newline
() show newline
