(18.3 Heritage) show newline
(-------------) show newline
() show newline
(The three original residents honor the lineage of text editing:) show newline
() show newline
(  * TECO \(1962\) - Dan Murphy at MIT. Every keystroke a command. EMACS was written in TECO before it was written in anything else.) show newline
(  * Electric Pencil \(1976\) - Michael Shrayer. First word processor for microcomputers, predates WordStar by two years.) show newline
(  * Schemacs \(2026\) - ddp & Claude, inspired by guenchi/Schemacs \(Chez Scheme\). Emacs keybindings, Scheme soul. The collaboration continues.) show newline
() show newline
(Hemlock \(1987\) - Bill Chiles and Rob MacLachlan at CMU. An Emacs-like) show newline
(editor written entirely in Common Lisp for CMU CL. Hemlock proved that a) show newline
(Lisp implementation could host its own extensible editor, the extension) show newline
(language and the implementation language being one and the same.) show newline
(Schemacs follows that tradition - the REPL is the extension language.) show newline
() show newline
(The credits in \(residents\) aren't decoration - they're acknowledgment.) show newline
(Dan Murphy's TECO ran on PDP-1s. Michael Shrayer's Electric Pencil ran) show newline
(on 8K Altairs. Now they run on Cyberspace, sixty years of heritage) show newline
(compressed into lambdas.) show newline
